So, result of some dives into NVIDIA's moat in AI accelerators:
This is a software moat. AMD's ROCm and everything Intel has done with SYCL is overall coming short (ROCm specifically is coming extremely short). Major consequence: none of the ML frameworks are by default optimized for either. It's probably easier to find resources, library support and optimization techniques for Apple Silicon (partly due to George Hotz's obsession).

People who don't know, Sutskever was in Google when he wrote the LSTM paper. This is a pre-requisite for imagining the value of "attention".

Excellent article with amazing writing.
"Interestingly it was Marx who predicted the inevitable end of the state brought down by the logic of the left. Today it is the implacable enemies of Marxism who predict the end of the state brought down by the logic of the right. Big business and globalisation is now the target of the right, while censorship is a go-to tool of the progressive left. The right has become left, and the left has become the right. Such blurring will continue.
Welcome to politics – new-age style."
As a classic late bloomer, I appreciate this framework.
Today's episode of 'If you criticize Israel, you are anti-Semitic'.
My friend upped the game right there...

Let's understand an analysis falacy.
Consultant cared births are the ones that's explicitly complicated, requiring care that's out of scope for Midwives. These are complex cases, filled with tensions, often requiring interventions and procedures.  End of the journey here is naturally not expected to be sweet, calm. At best, it's the end of a stressful period. 
Home birth is generally allowed only when you are a sure NVD case, no complications forecasted. It's end of an already known, smooth ride. 
Trying to compare the two experience is comparing apple to oranges.
Homebirth experiences more positive than hospital births, study finds

Wow.

Johny Harris couldn't find an external sponsor for the Qatar video. But youtube monetization technically facilitates these type of journalism. Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dt_Q03HNbTk
YouTube can do all this without being anywhere as controversial as other social media platform for a reason: YouTube policies are stable, balanced, deemed least unfair among most content creators and viewers while keeping some sanctity of information (ref [1]).
 Also, if YouTube recommendation doesn't seem super addictive as TikTok's or Facebook's, it's mostly due to conscious choices of not making the platform an ideological echo chamber.
A product I am truly proud of.
[1] https://www.nytimes.com/.../tiktok-youtube-facebook...

When it comes to self-driving car vision, the more I think about Elon Musk, the more I feel like he is just a mature Elizabeth Holmes. I don't think it's ever going to be doable safely without LIDAR and it's just going to sour the prospect for every other self-driving initiative.

Short-term thinking and narrow vision bring end to empires more than anything else.
Lufthansa and Munich airport were my favorite in 2019. The 90 euro round trip from DUB -> MUC -> HEL and ARN -> MUC -> DUB is still the best experience I ever had and the airport was a pleasure. Our own DUB airport's throughput awed me always, I never had to be in queue (from check-in to security done) more than 25mins until 2022. The record of check-in to flight seat in 16 mins (for an international flight) stands and I doubt any system can beat it.
If you make cuts, be ready to loose the best people first. The best people always find jobs and they never come back and you are always left with the bottom of the stack.
Taken to a new level.
On my way to home... Gonna be a fun month.

Something that stands out... "These people don't have much experience with democracy as we do..." "Ukrainians have had democracy for only a decade and look how hard they are fighting for it".
You fight for things you value. Unless you do, you probably don't true value it. Specially compare the contrasting view in Afghanistan.
We, in Bangladesh, valued freedom of speech and language in '52 and valued independence in '71. We fought for it. Democracy is indeed a lot of work. Someday I sure do hope we are ready for it...

Yesterday, a dog walker left untrained dog without leash and the dog came running barking aggressively and she was exactly like this, "he is friendly, he is friendly..."... in my mind I did go exactly  like Chelsea... "Please reconsider your friendships if that that dog seems friendly"...
Some small sacrifices...
Wow. That's a different level of elevation.

One point to note:
This আশিকুল ইসলাম বিটু, an example of human piece of shit, went on record saying, “আবরারকে শিবির সন্দেহে রাত আটটার দিকে হলের ২০১১ নম্বর কক্ষে ডেকে আনা হয়। সেখানে আমরা তার মোবাইলে ফেসবুক ও মেসেঞ্জার চেক করি।..."
WTF?! How the fuck they have authority to check someone else's Facebook or Messenger?! Alone on that point, why shouldn't this guy be jailed?
Also on that point, রাজনীতি এবং ছাত্রলীগের সাথে যারা বর্তমানে জড়িত, যাদেরকে আমি ব্যাক্তিগত ভাবে চিনি না, দয়া করে আমাকে ফেসবুক থেকে unfriend করে আমাকে সহায়তা করবেন। I have the right to safety and privacy.

Wanted to check this out for so long!
Prime with Optimus Prime

I did a session with David J Wetherall, who is co-author of the Computer Network book with Tanenbaum, today.
I explained to him how Loc/ID separation works, what is ILA, what virtualization looks like and how this can be valuable to us. At the end, I was telling him it means a lot to me to be able to present to him and brainstorm with him. He was simply surprised and said, 'you are too kind'. At the end of the meeting a mail followed that ended with names of few more people in Google, including Amin Vahdat's and asked me if I would like to explain them what I explained him. AND whether I would like to author a short note about Network Function Virtualization with him.
One of the good days of life.

One of the major architectural work I did about a year ago has been declared General Available (GA) in OpenStack. (Finally!)
Even though I think Openstack is dead, it's nice to have GA code in the Long Term Support release.
When an exec distance herself, you know deepshit is going on over there...

My journey in networking started the other way around. I started with SDN then went towards distributed networking (meaning the old way of networking). So, naturally, my view and attitude towards the distributed network is biased.
SDN makes so much sense... Implementation of it, however, hasn't been its friend.
While we have had the ability to introduce programmability in the network by decoupling Control Plane and Data Plane and changing the implementation of Control Plane to introduce new features, true programmability will always be subjected to how we can enforce the control and policy down to a single unit and to which granularity. A good granularity will involve programmability on how we view flows and packets, which basically means programmability of packet parser which is a part of Data Plane and resides in the forwarding device (e.g. switch, router).
The coolest guys in the networking faculty, namely Nick McKeown, Martin Casado et al introduced P4 exactly for that.
The only problem was software stack's inability to perform in comparison with ASICs (most of which are proprietary). So, everybody could guess that making this work would require coupling of state of art silicon with bests of software.
While Nick McKeown with Barefoot Networks, Inc. has been pushing from the silicon end of the problem with FPGAs and latest silicon technologies, Google has been playing this game from the software side.
Finally, a great step forward. This ONS would be interesting, very very interesting!
Finally, flat mates again!
So, the trailer is out...

When I was about to board the flight from San Francisco to Dhaka last August, I was really worried about the coming 4 months. For the first time I was going to be really workless. Being a workaholic, my biggest fear has been not having enough work!
Fast forward 3 months, I not only hopefully closed many unwanted holes. I have met someone who made me realize I am actually not workaholic, I just hadn't met the right person. Someone who makes me better at everything I am. Someone who made me realize that life is more than what I have been thinking it to be.
Believe me, it has been a long journey finding you Sadia Yeasmin Nipun, my beloved wife. 
There are sides of life you see only when you slow down. Slowdown and relax. Life has all kinds of surprises for you.
Sitting at airport to board the flight back to San Francisco gives me some moments to reflect back on last few months. Only one word comes in mind, 'internal peace'!
